   Reply. 
 The deposition of those Kings hath been resolved treason by all the Iudges of England;
Coke institut part. 2. tit. treason. and yet if it had been legall, the Presidents are impertinent, for those acts were confirmed by the Kings themselves, and could never have been esteemed acts of Parliament without their owne assent.

If it vvere the custome anciently to take such an oath as they alleadge, that custome is now abrogated and other formes are upon record, vvhich have been taken successively by many Kings together, and ought now to take place. Let not the Commons if they love their ovvne interest plead to have all ancient customes revived. But secondly I say, that there was never such a custome;
In the time of Henry the third the Kings oath conteined onely these three things.B • acton • . b. 3. cap. 9. 1. Se esse praecepturum, & pro viribus opem impensurum ut Ecclesiae Dei & omni populo Christiano vera pax, omni suo tempore observetur, 2. ut rapacitates & omnes iniquitates, omnibus gradibus interdicat, 3. ut in omnibus judiciis aequitatem praecipiat & misericordiam. Common practice doth also disprove such a custome; Kings have alwayes refused what bills they would, yet breach of oath was never objected against them untill these times. Now if the houses could shevv (which I beleeve they can not) that divers Kings have taken the foresaid oath, or any other bearing such a sence as they impose upon it, that is not sufficient to prove a custome seeing the practise was formerly, and is at the present otherwise. Thirdly if it be granted them that the sayd forme ought novv to be used, yet it vvill not admit of such an interpretation as they have given it; the vvorde Lawes in the oath can not be understood of those lavves vvhich shall afterwards be offered the King by the tvvo houses in Parliament, for that clause, quas vulgus elegerit, can not be applied to the house of Lords. Fourthly let it be yet further granted that the above said forme ought to be taken, and that the sence of it is such as they interpret, yet they bind him not to assent to all lawes, but onely to those that are just, and so farre he is bound in conscience to assent without an oath, and to that end he is assisted in Parliament
by his justices, and councell at lavv, vvho ought to in forme him, where he wanteth information, what are the rightes of the Crowne, vvhat the liberties of the people, that so he might be the better able to determine what is fit to be passed, and what is fit to be denyed.
